<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="187" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1409]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1204,1229]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name refers to the fawn ground colour of wings which is similar to that of a roe (
<emphasis box="[160,392,1240,1264]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Capreolus capreolus</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1409]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,443,1276,1301]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Taxonomic remarks</emphasis>
. The fawn ground colour is a rare character of the genus. It is shared only by an undescribed species from 
<collectingCountry box="[448,550,1312,1337]" name="Thailand" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, which is known only by one female specimen. The wing patterns of the two taxa have many similar elements, but the female is much larger and its forewing is much more elongate than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[181,313,1384,1408]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Naarda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capreola">
<emphasis box="[181,313,1384,1408]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">N. capreola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
